>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Attainment’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Lavedre","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jorge, Juan, Manuel, Adriana, Alvaro, Bernardo, Elena, Ezequiel, Francisca, Francisco, Jaime, Liliana.  Italian Dario, Leonardo, Salvatore.","Spanish; Italian (mainly <b>La Verde</b>): variant of   Verde   ‘green’, with (fused) definite article <i>la</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Verde","meanings":["Reduced form of   Gertrud ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Robert de Lavedre was born in 1190, in Scotland as the son of Robertus de Lavedre. He had at least 1 son."},"et":{"1190–":"1190–Surnud","1190–Male":"1190–Surnud","1210–1251":"1210–1251","1158–Male":"1158–Surnud","1190":"1190","1158":"1158","1210":"1210","1251":"1251","Scotland":"Scotland"},"fi":{"1190–":"1190–Kuollut","1190–Male":"1190–Kuollut","1210–1251":"1210–1251","1158–Male":"1158–Kuollut","1190":"1190","1158":"1158","1210":"1210","1251":"1251","Scotland":"Scotland"},"fr":{"1190–":"1190–Décédé","1190–Male":"1190–Décédé","1210–1251":"1210–1251","1158–Male":"1158–Décédé","1190":"1190","1158":"1158","1210":"1210","1251":"1251","Scotland":